Model decision anamnessis

Session title: ad hoc meeting
Date: 14/09/2021
Editor: Eugeniu Costetchi, Natalie Muric

Example awarding (instance level)

init

Organisation_P playsRole Tenderer_X in Procedure_0 .
Organisation_Q playsRole Tenderer_Y in Procedure_0 .
Organisation_R playsRole Tenderer_Z in Procedure_0 .

Lot_1

TenderLot_B is submitted by Tenderer_X (to the Buyer/Requester) for Lot_1.
Lot_1 is (awarded)attributed to TenderLot_B with rank 1 (by the Awarder which is the organisation of the Buyer).
Lot_1 is awarded to Tenderer_X for/based_on its TenderLot_B, which is ranked 1.
Therefore the Tenderer_X becomes Winner_X (with TenderLot_B).
Therefore the Winner_X is ranked 1 (with)based_on TenderLot_B.

TenderLot_C is submitted by the Tenderer_Y (to the Buyer/Requester) for Lot_1.
Lot_1 is awarded to TenderLot_C with rank 2.
Lot_1 is awarded to Tenderer_Y for/based_on its TenderLot_C, which is ranked 2.
Therefore the Tenderer_Y becomes Winner_Y (with TenderLot_C).
Therefore the Winner_Y is ranked 2 (with)based_on TenderLot_C.
TenderLot_C is awarded (to the Submitter thus turning Tenderer_Y into Winner_Y) (by the Awarder which is the organisation of the Buyer).

TenderLot_A is submitted by Tenderer_X (to the Buyer/Requester) for Lot_1.
Lot_1 is awarded to TenderLot_A with rank 3.
Lot_1 is awarded to Tenderer_X for/based_on its TenderLot_A, which is ranked 3.
Therefore the Tenderer_X becomes Winner_X (with TenderLot_A).
Therefore the Winner_X is ranked 3 with/based_on TenderLot_A.
TenderLot_A is awarded (to the submitter thus turning Tenderer_X into Winner_X) (by the Awarder which is the organisation of the Buyer) .

Lot_2

Lot_2 is not awarded.

Lot 3

TenderLot_D is submitted by Tenderer_Y (to the Buyer/Requester) for Lot_3.
Lot_3 is awarded to the TenderLot_D with rank 1.
Lot_3 is awarded to Tenderer_Y based_on its TenderLot_D, which is ranked 1.
Therefore the Tenderer_Y becomes Winner_Y (with TenderLot_D).
Therefore the Winner_Y is ranked 1 based_on TenderLot_D.

TenderLot_E is submitted by Tenderer_X (to the Buyer/Requester) for Lot_3.
Lot_3 is awarded to the TenderLot_E with rank 2.
Lot_3 is awarded to Tenderer_X based_on its TenderLot_E, which is ranked 2.
Therefore the Tenderer_X becomes Winner_X (with TenderLot_E).
Therefore the Winner_X is ranked 2 based_on TenderLot_E.

TenderLot_F is submitted by Tenderer_Z (to the Buyer/Requester) for Lot_3.
Lot_3 is awarded to the TenderLot_F with rank 3.
Lot_3 is awarded to Tenderer_Z based_on its TenderLot_F, which is ranked 3.
Therefore the Tenderer_Z becomes Winner_Z (with TenderLot_F).
Therefore the Winner_Z is ranked 3 based_on TenderLot_F.

Competency questions

  • Who is the winner of Lot_3?

  • Who are the winners of Lot_3 and with which rank?

  • Which Organisation is the primary winner of each lot?

  • Who is Lot_3 awarded to?

  • Who is Lot_2 awarded to? == Terminological clarifications

Situation

Definitions:

  • (Oxford dictionary) a set of circumstances in which one finds oneself; a state of affairs. (DUL class Situation) A view, consistent with ('satisfying') a Description, on a set of entities.

    • It can also be seen as a 'relational context' created by an observer on the basis of a 'frame' (i.e. a Description).

    • For example, a PlanExecution is a context including some actions executed by agents according to certain parameters and expected tasks to be achieved from a Plan; a DiagnosedSituation is a context of observed entities that is interpreted on the basis of a Diagnosis, etc.

    • Situation is also able to represent reified n-ary relations, where isSettingFor is the top-level relation for all binary projections of the n-ary relation.

    • If used in a transformation pattern for n-ary relations, the designer should take care of adding (some or all) OWL2 keys, corresponding to binary projections of the n-ary, to a subclass of Situation. Otherwise the 'identification constraint' (Calvanese et al., IJCAI 2001) might be violated

  • (DUL hasSetting/isSettingFor (Entity<→Situation)) A relation between entities and situations,

    • e.g. 'this morning I’ve prepared my coffee with a new fantastic Arabica', i.e.: (an amount of) a new fantastic Arabica hasSetting the preparation of my coffee this morning.

  • (LOTED2 class SubjectiveLegalSituation) A subjective legl situation is any position held by a natural or legal person, characterized by a role played in a given context.

    • A person may have one or more subjective legal situations.

    • For example a body governed by public law may have the position of contracting authority in the tender X, but may have the position of tenderer in the tender Y. === Participation

Definitions:

  • (Oxford dictionary) the action of taking part in something

  • (DUL property isParticipantIn/hasParticipant (Object<→Event)) A relation between an object and a process,

    • e.g. 'John took part in the discussion',

    • 'a large mass of snow fell during the avalanche', or

    • 'a cook, some sugar, flour, etc. are all present in the cooking of a cake'. === Role

Definitions:

  • (Oxford dictionary) the function assumed or part played by a person or thing in a particular situation.

    • Syn: capacity, duty, position

  • (DUL class Role) A Concept that classifies an Object.

  • (DUL property isRoleOf/hasRole (Role<→Object)) A relation between an object and a role, e.g. 'student' is the role of 'John'.

    • Subproperty of isClassifiedBy (A relation between a Concept and an Entity, e.g. 'John is considered a typical rude man'; your last concert constitutes the achievement of a lifetime; '20-year-old means she’s mature enough')

  • (DUL property definedRole/isRoleDefinedIn (Description<→Role) )A relation between a description and a role, e.g. the recipe for a cake defines the role 'ingredient'. (PRO class Role) A role an agent may have. Individual members of this class or its sub-classes are used to specify particular roles.

  • (LOTED2 class Role) A role is a specification of default behavior and accompanying expectations of the thing 'playing' the role. Similar to actors in a theater who play roles, but are not the roles. Example: student (Source: LKIF-core ontology)

  • (LOTED2 class LegalRole) A legal role is a role played in a legal context. Legal role players can be both Agents and other 'things' (Source: LKIF-core ontology). === Function

  • (Oxford dictionary) an activity that is natural to or the purpose of a person or thing.

    • Syns: role, purpose, reason, use

  • (LOTED2 class Function) The use or purpose of some object as used in some context (Source: LKIF-core ontology).

RoleInTime

Definitions:

  • (PRO class RoleInTime) A particular situation that describe a role an agent may have, that can be restricted to a particular time interval.

    • A role in time describes always:

      • a particular role R

      • a particular agent A holding R

      • a particular time interval T in which A holds R (optional)

      • one or more entities (e.g. a particular bibliographic entity or a specific institution) that defines a context for R held by A. (At least one contextual entity should be specified for a particular role).

  • (PRO relation holdsRoleInTime (Agent<→hasRoleInTime)) === Action

Definitions:

  • (Oxford dictionary) the fact or process of doing something, typically to achieve an aim

  • (DUL class Action) An Event with at least one Agent that isParticipantIn it, and that executes a Task that typically isDefinedIn a Plan, Workflow, Project, etc. === Process

Definitions:

  • (Oxford definition) a series of actions or steps taken in order to achieve a particular end.

  • (Oxford definition) a natural series of changes.

  • (DUL class Process) This is a placeholder for events that are considered in their evolution, or anyway not strictly dependent on agents, tasks, and plans. See Event class for some thoughts on classifying events. See also 'Transition'. == Few references:

ParticipantRole DP

http://ontologydesignpatterns.org/wiki/Submissions:ParticipantRole

RoleInTime from PRO

https://sparontologies.github.io/pro/current/pro.html#classes

Participation

https://github.com/catalogue-of-services-isa/CPSV-AP

SocialReality pattern

In [Hoekstra 2010-Social reality in OWL]

P2: LOTED2 - Subjective Legal Situations and Roles

Social reality pattern in LOTED2
